famous warrior-king Gesar. In their rampage the mob attacked, mutilated, and killed county officials and local villagers as well as People's Liberation Army troops. This groundbreaking book, the first on the Cultural Revolution in Tibet, revisits the Nyemo Incident, which has long been romanticized as the epitome of Tibetan nationalist resistance against China. Melvyn C. Goldstein, Ben Jiao, and Tanzen Lhundrup demonstrate that far from being a spontaneous battle for independence, this violent event was actually part of a struggle between rival revolutionary groups and was not ethnically based. On the Cultural Revolution in Tibet proffers a sober assessment of human malleability and challenges the tendency to view every sign of unrest in Tibet in ethno-nationalist terms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  a20th century tibetan history.  abagor district.  achina.  achinese imperialism.  achinese occupation.  acombat.  aconflict.  acultural revolution in tibet.  acultural revolution.  adeity.  agyenlo.  aindependence.  alhasa.  amob.  anationalist resistance.  anyamdre.  anyemo.  apeoples liberation army.  apolitical.  apossession.  arevolutionaries.  arival revolutionary groups.  atibet sovereignty debate.  atibet.  atibetan history.  atibetan nationalism.  aviolence.  awarrior king gesar.  ayoung nun.1 aJiao, Ben, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLhundrup, Tanzen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025682840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094238740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520942387423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.